{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Failure boundary is the model’s actual content selection, not just local wiring. A mocked/stubbed model can be forced to echo specifics and would hide real failures where the live model returns vague/generic text. Unit would miss prompt+context formatting effects on real model behavior; Integration would miss relevance failures caused by real LLM judgment variability. Workflow was considered but rejected: behavior text checks one generation outcome, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Run generation against a real LLM on a fixture email thread containing 3-4 concrete points (dates, asks, constraints). Assert the draft explicitly references at least two thread-specific points and is not a template-like generic response; repeat across multiple seeds/runs to detect instability.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior can be validated at module handoff level: draft-claim extraction/lookup/checker logic against a local KB fixture. Concrete Unit-miss: a schema/key mismatch between checker and KB adapter causes contradictions to be missed even though each function passes in isolation. System was considered and rejected: behavior text does not require real network/OS/subprocess. Agentic was considered and rejected: text does not require real model-quality judgment; it specifies contradiction detection against KB entries, which can be exercised deterministically.","test_description":"Wire checker + KB repository with an in-process test KB. Feed a draft containing known contradictory claims and assert contradiction flags include expected claim IDs/evidence references; include a control claim that should not be flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.13,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on live LLM behavior under missing-context conditions (hallucination vs disclaimer). A stubbed model would always return the expected disclaimer and hide real fabrication failures. Unit would miss prompt-conditioning failures; Integration with deterministic fixtures would miss true model tendency to invent details. Workflow was considered but rejected: this behavior focuses on one model decision (how to draft when KB is empty), not multi-agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Use a real LLM with KB retrieval returning empty/no-relevance for a thread that invites factual statements. Assert the draft contains the required uncertainty disclaimer and no unsupported concrete facts; run multiple trials to catch non-deterministic hallucinations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is state handoff/orchestration between draft state, approval gate, and sender module. Concrete Unit-miss: each function may pass alone, but event wiring can trigger sender before approval flag persists. System was considered and rejected: real email provider/network is not required to catch this gate violation; an in-process sender spy is sufficient. Agentic/Workflow rejected: behavior does not depend on model output quality or sequential agentic decisions.","test_description":"Exercise workflow with draft-created state and simulated user actions. Verify sender is not invoked before explicit approval event, then verify sender is invoked exactly once after approval.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets full pipeline execution with an LLM generation step plus downstream fact-check and approval stages. Lower levels miss cross-stage failures where model output shape/content causes later stages to fail or bypass checks. Concrete Integration-miss: stubbing the model can hide failures where real generated wording prevents claim extraction/fact check from triggering. Concrete Agentic-miss: single-step agentic tests do not validate multi-stage handoff across the entire pipeline. System-only is insufficient because agentic decision quality is in scope.","test_description":"Run an end-to-end scenario on a real email thread: ingest thread, call real LLM for draft, run real fact-check path, present approval UI/state, and confirm send remains blocked until approval. Assert stage outputs and handoff invariants across the full chain.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.65}}]}
